The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Mumbai, Jan. 10: The Securities and Exchange Board of India will focus on developing the debt market over the next two years. It is concerned at the low growth rate in this segment, which, it feels, is as important as the one dealing in equity. ?Both are crucial for the growth of the entire capital market,? Sebi chief G. N. Bajpai told a conference organised by ICFAI here today.

 New Delhi, Jan. 10: Nasscom today said inadequate infrastructure in the country had begun to hurt the IT sector. ?Lack of proper infrastructure is becoming a matter of concern for the IT and IT-enabled services sector,? Nasscom president Kiran Karnik said today. Another challenge before the industry was to make the country a destination for IT products, he added.

 Calcutta, Jan. 10: Tata Tea has sought the permission of the Tea Board to start facilities for packaging tea bags at Indore and Calcutta. Tata Tea managing director Percy T. Siganporia said the response to Tetley?s four Indianised flavours of tea bags was good.

 Coimbatore, Jan. 10: With the phasing out of the quota regime, the textile sector needs Rs 27,000 crore to compete globally, said finance minister P. Chidambaram.

 Kochi, Jan. 10: Lord Krishna Bank will soon launch a Rs 46-crore rights issue. The issue would be open to all 11,000 shareholders and the shares, priced at Rs 12, would be at a premium of Rs 2.




